Entropic Regularization of Optimal Transport

Important: Please read the installation page for details about how to install the toolboxes.

This numerical tours exposes the general methodology of regularizing the optimal transport (OT) linear program using entropy. This allows to derive fast computation algorithm based on iterative projections according to a Kulback-Leiber divergence.

Entropic Regularization of Optimal Transport

We consider two input histograms a,bna,bn, where we denote the simplex in RnRn

n{aRn+,iai=1}.n{aR+n,iai=1}.
We consider the following discrete regularized transport
W(a,b)minPU(a,b)C,PE(P).W(a,b)minPU(a,b)C,PE(P).
where the polytope of coupling is defined as
U(a,b){P(R+)nm,PIm=a,PIn=b},U(a,b){P(R+)nm,PIm=a,PIn=b},
where In(1,,1)RnIn(1,,1)Rn, and for PRnm+PR+nm, we define its entropy as
E(P)i,jPi,j(log(Pi,j)1).E(P)i,jPi,j(log(Pi,j)1).

When =0=0 one recovers the classical (discrete) optimal transport. We refer to the monograph Villani for more details about OT. The idea of regularizing transport to allows for faster computation is introduced in Cuturi.

Here the matrix C(R+)nmC(R+)nm defines the ground cost, i.e. Ci,jCi,j is the cost of moving mass from a bin indexed by ii to a bin indexed by jj.

The regularized transportation problem can be re-written as a projection

W(a,b)=minPU(a,b)KL(P|K)whereKi,jeCi,jW(a,b)=minPU(a,b)KL(P|K)whereKi,jeCi,j
of the Gibbs kernel KK according to the Kullback-Leibler divergence. The Kullback-Leibler divergence between P,KRnm+P,KR+nm is
KL(P|K)i,jPi,j(log(Pi,jKi,j)1).KL(P|K)i,jPi,j(log(Pi,jKi,j)1).

This interpretation of regularized transport as a KL projection and its numerical applications are detailed in BenamouEtAl.

Given a convex set CRNCRN, the projection according to the Kullback-Leiber divergence is defined as

ProjKLC()=argminCKL(|).ProjCKL()=argminCKL(|).

Iterative Bregman Projection Algorithm

Given affine constraint sets (C1,C2)(C1,C2), we aim at computing

ProjKLC(K)whereC=C1C2ProjCKL(K)whereC=C1C2
(this description can of course be extended to more than 2 sets).

This can be achieved, starting by P0=KP0=K, by iterating 00,

P2+1=ProjKLC1(P2)andP2+2=ProjKLC2(P2+1).P2+1=ProjC1KL(P2)andP2+2=ProjC2KL(P2+1).

One can indeed show that PProjKLC(K)PProjCKL(K). We refer to BauschkeLewis for more details about this algorithm and its extension to compute the projection on the intersection of convex sets (Dikstra algorithm).

Sinkhorn's Algorithm

A fundamental remark is that the optimality condition of the entropic regularized problem shows that the optimal coupling PP necessarily has the form

P=diag(u)Kdiag(v)P=diag(u)Kdiag(v)
where the Gibbs kernel is defined as
KeC.KeC.

One thus needs to find two positive scaling vectors uRn+uR+n and vRm+vR+m such that the two following equality holds

PI=u(Kv)=aandPI=v(Ku)=b.PI=u(Kv)=aandPI=v(Ku)=b.

Sinkhorn's algorithm alternate between the resolution of these two equations, and reads

uaKvandvbKu.uaKvandvbKu.
This algorithm was shown to converge to a solution of the entropic regularized problem by Sinkhorn.

One can compute an approximation of the transport plan between the two measure by computing the so-called barycentric projection map

ti[0,1]sjjPi,jtjjPi,j=[uK(vt)]jai.ti[0,1]sjjPi,jtjjPi,j=[uK(vt)]jai.
where and are the enry-wise multiplication and division.

This computation can thus be done using only multiplication with the kernel KK.

When using Pytorch, it is good practice to implement matrix operation as summation and dummy variables. We show here how to implement one iteration of Sinkhorn this way.

In [18]:
u = a1 / (K1 * v[None,:]).sum(1)
v = b1 / (K1 * u[:,None]).sum(0)

Exercise:

Implement the full algorithm.

In [19]:
v = torch.ones(N)
niter = 2000
Err_p = torch.zeros(niter)
Err_q = torch.zeros(niter)
for i in range(niter):
    # sinkhorn step 1
    u = a1 / (K1 * v[None,:]).sum(1)    
    # error computation
    r = v*(K1 * u[:,None]).sum(0)
    Err_q[i] = torch.norm(r - b1, p=1)
    # sinkhorn step 2
    v = b1 / (K1 * u[:,None]).sum(0)
    s = u*(K1 * v[None,:]).sum(1)
    Err_p[i] = torch.norm(s - a1,p=1)
plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
plt.subplot(2,1,1)
plt.title("$||P1 -a||_1$")
plt.plot(np.log(np.asarray(Err_p)), linewidth = 2)
plt.subplot(2,1,2)
plt.title("$||P^T 1 -b||_1$")
plt.plot(np.log(np.asarray(Err_q)), linewidth = 2)
plt.show()

Exercice To avoid underflow, replace the matrix/vector multiplication in a log-sum-exp style, and use the log-sum-exp stabilization trick.

Wasserstein Barycenters

Instead of computing transport, we now turn to the problem of computing barycenter of RR input measures (ak)Rk=1(ak)k=1R. A barycenter bb solves

minbk=1RW(ak,b)minbk=1RW(ak,b)
where kk are positive weights with kk=1kk=1. This follows the definition of barycenters proposed in AguehCarlier.

Dimension (width of the images) NN of the histograms.

In this specific case, the kernel KK associated with the squared Euclidean norm is a convolution with a Gaussian filter

Ki,j=ei/Nj/N2/Ki,j=ei/Nj/N2/
where here (i,j)(i,j) are 2-D indexes.

The multiplication against the kernel, i.e. K(a)K(a), can now be computed efficiently, using fast convolution methods. This crucial points was exploited and generalized in SolomonEtAl to design fast optimal transport algorithm.

Regularization strength >0>0.

In [44]:
epsilon = (.04)**2

Define the KK kernel. We use here the fact that the convolution is separable to implement it using only 1-D convolution, which further speeds up computations.

In [45]:

[Y,X] = np.meshgrid(t,t)
K1 = np.exp(-(X-Y)**2/epsilon)
K = lambda x: np.dot(np.dot(K1,x),K1)

Weights kk for isobarycenter.

In [47]:
lambd = np.ones(R)/R

It is shown in BenamouEtAl that the problem of Barycenter computation boilds down to optimizing over couplings (Pk)Rk=1(Pk)k=1R, and that this can be achieved using iterative a Sinkhorn-like algorithm, since the optimal coupling has the scaling form

Pk=diag(uk)Kdiag(vk)Pk=diag(uk)Kdiag(vk)
for some unknown positive weights (uk,vk)(uk,vk).

Initialize the scaling factors (uk,vk)k(uk,vk)k, store them in matrices.

In [48]:
v = np.ones([N,N,R])
u = np.copy(v)

The first step of the Bregman projection method corresponds to the projection on the fixed marginals constraints PkI=akPkI=ak. This is achieved by updating

k=1,,R,ukakK(vk).k=1,,R,ukakK(vk).

In [49]:
for k in range(R):
    u[:,:,k] = A[:,:,k]/K(v[:,:,k])

The second step of the Bregman projection method corresponds to the projection on the equal marginals constraints k,PkI=bk,PkI=b for a common barycenter target bb. This is achieved by first computing the target barycenter bb using a geometric means

log(b)kklog(ukK(vk)).log(b)kklog(ukK(vk)).

In [50]:
b = np.zeros(N)
for k in range(R):
    b = b + lambd[k] * np.log(np.maximum(1e-19*np.ones(len(v[:,:,k])), v[:,:,k]*K(u[:,:,k])))
b = np.exp(b)

And then one can update the scaling by a Sinkhorn step using this newly computed histogram bb as follow (note that K=KK=K here):

k=1,,R,vkbK(uk).k=1,,R,vkbK(uk).

for k in range(R):
    v[:,:,k] = b/K(u[:,:,k])
